      Bitcoin garbage guy
   =20
 =20
Earlier this year we talked about a guy in Wales named James Howells who th=
rew out a hard drive with 8,000 Bitcoins on it back when Bitcoin was just a=
 hobby, and now that those Bitcoins are worth hundreds of millions of dolla=
rs he is crusading to dig up the garbage dump to find the hard drive. This =
is an irresistible subject for jokes, and I made some jokes about it that y=
ou can read  here and  here.Here is a New Yorker profile of the guy, who I =
think it is safe to say is=C2=A0much=C2=A0worse off for being a Bitcoin-mil=
lionaire-but-they=E2=80=99re-in-a-dump than he would be if he had never had=
 the thousands of Bitcoins:He told me that his children were into other thi=
ngs now, and didn=E2=80=99t visit anymore. He did not wish to discuss any r=
omantic relationships that he=E2=80=99d had since Hafina left. =E2=80=9CI t=
ry to keep to myself,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CWomen are costly.=E2=80=
=9DHowells was no longer employed. For more than a year after the loss of t=
he hard drive, he had continued at his job as a systems engineer. To make t=
he workday tolerable, he=E2=80=99d limited how often he consulted the bitco=
in-tracking app. He=E2=80=99d even tried to avoid driving routes that took =
him by the dump. But, eventually, the memory of the money he had thrown awa=
y overpowered his work ethic. =E2=80=9CI kind of lost the motivation,=E2=80=
=9D he explained.Also he constantly checks how much his lost Bitcoins are w=
orth and=C2=A0worries he might get robbed because he=E2=80=99s a Bitcoin ce=
lebrity.I have  joked enough about the =E2=80=9Cobject-fire-token-money=E2=
=80=9D cycle of non-fungible tokens to say that the obvious solution here i=
s that Howells should mint a non-fungible token representing, like, =E2=80=
=9CI threw away 8,000 Bitcoins.=E2=80=9D This would have two benefits:=09He=
=E2=80=99d own a tangible (ish) thing representing his Bitcoins in the dump=
, which might make him feel better, and=09Maybe he could sell it? Or a shar=
e of it? How much would an NFT representing 8,000 vanished Bitcoins be wort=
h? Search me, but maybe something?But actually you don=E2=80=99t need to ge=
t into the metaphysics of NFTs to do this; this is just regular finance. Ri=
ght now Howells has some sort of=C2=A0claim to those lost Bitcoins. That cl=
aim is not worth 8,000 Bitcoins or anything close to it, because:=09Nobody =
has possession of the hard drive; it=E2=80=99s somewhere in the dump.=09Act=
ually you can=E2=80=99t be 100% sure it=E2=80=99s even in the dump? Maybe a=
 seagull carried it away, or everyone=E2=80=99s memory of throwing it in th=
e dump is wrong, I don=E2=80=99t know.=09The town of Newport, which runs=C2=
=A0the dump, has emphatically denied his requests to dig up the dump to fin=
d the hard drive and doesn=E2=80=99t seem likely to budge on that.=09Even i=
f you did find it in the dump, it might have decayed to the point where his=
 private key is not recoverable.=09Even if the town authorities=C2=A0change=
 their mind, he digs up the dump, he finds the hard drive, it works, his ke=
y is on it, and he recovers the 8,000 Bitcoins, many of those Bitcoins have=
 been promised to someone else at this point: =E2=80=9CHe met with potentia=
l investors, and eventually made arrangements with two European businessmen=
 who agreed to support a recovery operation. Howells would get only about a=
 third of the proceeds. He had hoped for a much higher sum; the money was h=
is, after all. He recalls being told, =E2=80=98James, that=E2=80=99s not ho=
w it works.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D (Also: =E2=80=9Che made a public offer to giv=
e Newport a twenty-five-per-cent cut of the proceeds=E2=80=9D if they appro=
ved his dig.)=09It is not clear to me what his legal ownership of the hard =
drive is; if I snuck into the dump at night, found the hard drive myself an=
d took it, could anyone demand it=C2=A0from me? It was thrown away; who own=
s it? Or if I formed my own consortium of diggers and promised Newport a 50=
% cut of the proceeds, and Newport let me dig, would Howells have any claim=
 to stop me?Still! Howells=E2=80=99s murky contingent residual claim =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cif I get permission to dig up this dump and=C2=A0if=C2=A0=
I find this hard drive and=C2=A0if we find the=C2=A0Bitcoins on it and=C2=
=A0after I pay off everyone else, I=E2=80=99ll have some Bitcoins left=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems like it might be valuable? It is somewhat bette=
r than a lottery ticket. There is some imaginable future =E2=80=94=C2=A0he=
=C2=A0certainly imagines it, and he=E2=80=99s convinced some people to back=
 him=C2=A0financially =E2=80=94=C2=A0where he actually digs up the hard dri=
ve and gets (some of) the Bitcoins and his stake is worth, you know, $120 m=
illion. If there=E2=80=99s a 5% chance of that happening then that chance i=
s worth like $6 million. Maybe someone would pay him $3 million for a 50% s=
hare of his claim? He=E2=80=99s got a potentially valuable asset, which, by=
 the rules of finance, means that he=E2=80=99s got an=C2=A0actually=C2=A0va=
luable asset.=C2=A0Why not sell it? Isn=E2=80=99t that better=C2=A0than han=
ging on to it obsessively?
