Sometime before the 2008 financial crisis,=C2=A0an investor named Brian She=
ehy shorted the stock of a small bank called Capital Corp of the West, bett=
ing that it would go bankrupt. He was right.=C2=A0CCOW=C2=A0went extremely =
bankrupt, bankrupt enough that I can=E2=80=99t easily find a stock price ch=
art. Here is the final Form 8-K that CCOW filed with the U.S. Securities an=
d Exchange Commission, noting that CCOW liquidated in bankruptcy and its st=
ock vanished in early 2010:The Company has concluded that because there are=
 insufficient funds to pay all claims in full, common shareholders=E2=80=99=
 interests in the Debtor will be cancelled by the Plan and, accordingly, no=
 distribution will be available for common shareholders. Pursuant to Sectio=
n 4.5 of the Second Amended Liquidation Plan, all of the Company=E2=80=99s =
shares, warrants and stock options were cancelled as of the close of busine=
ss on February 4, 2010. Accordingly, the Company intends to file a Form 15 =
to terminate the Company=E2=80=99s registration under Section 12(g) of the =
Securities Exchange Act of 1934.Sheehy scored a win and moved on with his l=
ife. He started a new hedge fund, IsZo Capital Management LP, in about 2010=
.[1] In 2016, he moved IsZo=E2=80=99s account from a previous prime broker =
to Jefferies Group LLC. In 2021 he moved the account from Jefferies to anot=
her prime broker. Jefferies kept some of IsZo=E2=80=99s money, though, as c=
ollateral for positions that it couldn=E2=80=99t close or move to the new p=
rime broker. One of those positions was apparently the CCOW short, a stock =
that had gone to zero and vanished a decade earlier, a position that I gues=
s IsZo had inherited from Sheehy=E2=80=99s previous investments and brought=
 over to Jefferies.=C2=A0IsZo wants its money back, and has filed an arbitr=
ation claim against Jefferies.=C2=A0We  talked about it last month.=C2=A0No=
w IsZo=C2=A0has made some of its claims public in a letter to Jefferies tha=
t it put in a press release. The gist of it is that Jefferies is hanging on=
 to some of IsZo=E2=80=99s money to collateralize short positions in defunc=
t securities, and it shouldn=E2=80=99t be. For instance:In truth, there is =
no market for these worthless positions that do not, in reality, exist and =
none of these positions will ever trade again and simply cannot be closed b=
ecause the securities no longer exist. =E2=80=A6The four equity positions (=
Capital Corp. of the West, Franklin Credit Management Corp., CPI Corp. and =
Orleans Homebuilders) were in companies that filed for bankruptcy years ago=
. For example, Capital Corp of the West was shut down and liquidated over 1=
3 years ago! None of these cases resulted in common stockholders receiving =
new equity after the companies emerged from bankruptcy. Yet Jefferies conti=
nues to require cash collateral and charge short interest rebate for these =
positions that no longer exist in any shape or form. ...Jefferies' own Port=
folio Margin Detail (Report Date: 10/19/2021) for the seven legacy short po=
sitions shows a collective Market Price of 0.0000, a Market Value of (200.0=
0), a Delta Exposure of nothing, a Volatility of nothing and a Trading Volu=
me/Open Interest of nothing. Plainly, there is no market for these position=
s, to the extent they even can be said to "exist," and no justification to =
misappropriate millions of IsZo Capital's funds.It is weird to have to coll=
ateralize a short position in a stock that disappeared a decade ago but you=
 never know I guess?As we have discussed before, this is a risk of short se=
lling. If you correctly predict a stock will go down by 50%, you can sell i=
t at $100 and then buy=C2=A0it back at $50, making $50 of profit. If you co=
rrectly predict that it will go down by 99.99%, you can sell it at $100 and=
 buy it back at $0.01, making $99.99 of profit.If you correctly predict tha=
t it will go down by 100%, though, stuff gets weird. You probably can=E2=80=
=99t buy it back at $0. Theoretically the result is that you sold the stock=
 for $100 and then you never have to buy it back, because it disappeared: W=
hoever loaned you the stock doesn=E2=80=99t want it back, so you don=E2=80=
=99t have to buy back any stock, so you=C2=A0have $100 of profit and everyt=
hing is great. But that leaves sort of a nagging loose end: Your prime brok=
er thinks you still owe someone stock, but there=E2=80=99s no stock to deli=
ver, so it keeps your collateral and charges you fees forever.It doesn=E2=
=80=99t help that (1) as a stock approaches zero it will often become prett=
y illiquid, so buying it back at $0.01 may be hard to do,[2] and (2) if you=
 run a $300 million fund you might not be all that focused on spending like=
 $200 to buy back the now-worthless stock you shorted. Until a=C2=A0decade =
later=C2=A0when you notice you=E2=80=99ve been paying borrow fees the whole=
 time.Meanwhile if IsZo is still borrowing this nonexistent stock then is s=
omeone else still long it? Is someone somewhere collecting a stock-borrow f=
ee for lending out phantom CCOW stock to phantom=C2=A0short sellers? That=
=E2=80=99s some real long-term investing.
