   =20
      Pimco
   =20
 =20
I kind of like this level of commitment:"I have been shouted at, within two=
 feet of my face, in front of the office. The interview process could be ag=
gressive to the point of people crying," this person said, adding that empl=
oyees also cried during mock client presentations as well as during year-en=
d reviews.That is from a Business Insider story about the culture at Pacifi=
c Investment Management Co. I doubt there are too many big financial firms =
where nobody cries during year-end reviews; you=E2=80=99re kind of supposed=
 to cry during year-end reviews. Crying during job interviews strikes me as=
 weirder =E2=80=94=C2=A0make them cry after you hire them! =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut I can see it.But =E2=80=9Cmock client presentations=E2=80=9D? When I was=
 in a client-facing financial-services job I don=E2=80=99t think I ever did=
 a mock client presentation, and in hindsight I hate myself for that. Of co=
urse I should have been doing mock client presentations to prepare for real=
 client presentations!=C2=A0Of course those mock client presentations shoul=
d have been so ludicrously rigorous that they left me in tears! Then you go=
 to the real client presentation and you handle all of their questions with=
 ease, because you were so over-prepared for the terrifying=C2=A0mock prese=
ntation, and also you are warm and charming and personable and excited to b=
e there because=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s so much nicer to be with clients than wit=
h your colleagues. =E2=80=9CI really felt a connection with them,=E2=80=9D =
you say after the client meeting; =E2=80=9Cthey didn=E2=80=99t make me cry =
once.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s like swinging a weighted bat in the on-deck cir=
cle before stepping up to the plate, where the weight is your colleagues be=
ing mean.[3]=C2=A0Anyway here=E2=80=99s another financial-services-industry=
 business practice that I didn=E2=80=99t know about but that is intuitive o=
nce you see it:NEPC, a consulting firm that advises some of the world's big=
gest institutions on how and where to invest their money =E2=80=A6 brought =
five of its most senior people to the call [with Pimco], including its chie=
f investment officer and its director of investment manager research. The g=
roup also included members of NEPC's unfavorable news committee, created in=
 early 2019 to assess non-investment-related problems at money managers =E2=
=80=94 like sexual harassment and drug use =E2=80=94 that could affect firm=
s and their clients, according to an NEPC presentation.=C2=A0The NEPC execu=
tives wanted to address the growing laundry list of lawsuits and negative h=
eadlines hanging over Pimco. The month before, 21 women had sent a scathing=
 letter to the company's executive management team, sharply denouncing how =
it treats the women and people of color who work there. =C2=A0Sure yes if y=
ou are an investment consultant it is all well and good to tell your client=
s =E2=80=9Cthese are the managers who have good returns and these are the m=
anagers who have bad returns,=E2=80=9D but it is not clear how much value t=
hat adds. Telling your clients =E2=80=9Cthese are the managers who have dru=
g problems=E2=80=9D is clearly differentiated advice. On the other hand, if=
 your clients come to you and say =E2=80=9Chey I read in the newspaper that=
 the manager you recommended to me has a drug problem,=E2=80=9D that is goi=
ng to leave egg on your face; you need a rapid-response Bad News Committee =
to get to the bottom of any bad news about the managers you recommend. Kind=
 of a weird committee though. I=C2=A0assume that a lot of people would find=
 it unpleasant to be on the Bad News Committee, but a few people would find=
 it very pleasant indeed.A theme running through this Pimco story is what y=
ou might loosely call =E2=80=9Cgeneralized ESG.=E2=80=9D Investors =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0asset managers like Pimco, asset owners like Pimco=E2=80=99s custo=
mers, individual pension-plan beneficiaries, consultants, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0are interested not only in maximizing financial returns but also in sati=
sfying environmental, social and governance goals, broadly speaking. Some o=
f this might mean investing in stocks and bonds of companies with good ESG =
scores, but it is also important that your asset managers themselves be div=
erse and well-governed.If you run a public pension fund, you might care abo=
ut diversity and culture at the asset managers you hire because you think d=
iversity and culture matter for returns, or because you think that diversit=
y and culture are important for the world and you want to promote good thin=
gs in the world, or because you=C2=A0have a government=C2=A0mandate to prom=
ote diversity and good managerial cultures. Or because you run a public pen=
sion fund and so activists can FOIA everything you get from your asset mana=
gers:Some Pimco investors have found themselves on the receiving end of sub=
poenas and Freedom of Information Act requests for diversity statistics the=
y received from Pimco. Attorneys representing the plaintiffs in the ongoing=
 lawsuits alleged that the money manager has engaged in "diversity fraud" a=
nd said they served the legal documents to get answers.=C2=A0"The plaintiff=
s have issued subpoenas and freedom of information requests to Pimco client=
s to demand information that they never even requested from Pimco," [Pimco =
spokesperson Michael] Reid said in a statement. "As Pimco has argued in cou=
rt papers, 'diversity fraud' is not a recognized claim and Pimco has denied=
 the merits of this claim."Pension funds face activist pressure on diversit=
y, so they pressure their consultants, so their consultants pressure the as=
set managers, and so you end up with the Bad News Committee grilling Pimco =
about its diversity problems. I assume Pimco=E2=80=99s prep sessions for th=
is call were brutal.
