   =20
      Kickstarter
   =20
 =20
 Sure:For more than a decade, Kickstarter PBC has convinced the public to p=
ay people to follow through on their ideas to build a gadget, make a film o=
r create a piece of art. It was, in some ways, a harbinger of today=E2=80=
=99s digital economy built around cryptocurrencies, decentralized organizat=
ions and NFT art.On Wednesday, Kickstarter plans to unveil a project that w=
ill merge the two worlds. It=E2=80=99s hatching a standalone company to bui=
ld a crowdfunding system much like Kickstarter=E2=80=99s but based on block=
chain technology. When it=E2=80=99s ready, Kickstarter will switch its own =
website to the new infrastructure, and the new company will make the tools =
available for anyone to create a competing crowdfunding site.=E2=80=9CWe lo=
ve using Kickstarter to fund new projects,=E2=80=9D Kickstarter=E2=80=99s c=
ustomers presumably told it, =E2=80=9Cbut we worry that less than 100% of o=
ur money goes to transaction fees. We have seen that innovative blockchain =
technology has allowed decentralized platforms to raise millions of dollars=
 and=C2=A0spend absolutely all of it on transaction fees, and we want Kicks=
tarter to match that functionality.=E2=80=9D And so it will.Honestly imagin=
e watching  the ConstitutionDAO experience and thinking =E2=80=9Cah yes tha=
t is the way to fund projects from now on: Raise $40 million from small con=
tributors, fail to do the project, offer to return the money, and then have=
 huge chunks of it get burnt up in transaction fees.=E2=80=9D Yes! Terrific=
!=C2=A0The joke is that a blockchain is an expensive slow database, and als=
o it is not a joke, and also people=C2=A0desperately want that.
