      Anti-Fraud Jingle
   =20
 =20
The U.K. Financial Conduct Authority wrote a song. Its title appears to be =
=E2=80=9CAnti-Fraud Jingle.=E2=80=9D Here are the lyrics:My usually savvy b=
rother was offered a loanHis bank had turned him down, but he was desperate=
 for doughThey said =E2=80=9CJust pay a small amount and it=E2=80=99ll be o=
n the way=E2=80=9DBut the loan was never paid, and he knows he was playedFC=
A! Should=E2=80=99ve searched the person's details on theFCA=E2=80=99s! Fin=
ancial Services RegisterFCA! A list to check if there=E2=80=99s a problemFC=
A!So if you do get offered an enticing loanAn urgent upfront payment is a b=
ig "No, no"The Financial Services Register is your first port of callAnd if=
 the lender ain't legit, it's time to show them the doorFCA! Search the per=
son's details on theFCA=E2=80=99s Financial Services RegisterFCA! A list to=
 check if there=E2=80=99s a problemSpot scams and stop themBefore you borro=
w check theFCA!You can hear the FCA sing it here, and you should. The gener=
al problem with=C2=A0warnings against scams on regulatory websites is that =
the people who read the regulatory websites are generally not the people wh=
o were going=C2=A0to fall for the scams. I suppose the theory here is that =
the people who read regulatory websites will listen to this catchy jingle a=
nd then go around singing it in their daily lives, and then the people who=
=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0read regulatory websites but=C2=A0do=C2=A0fall for=
 scams will hear the jingle, and it will be so catchy that they ask =E2=80=
=9Cwhat is that=E2=80=9D and the other people will be=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Cit=
=E2=80=99s a cool new band called Financial Conduct Authority,=E2=80=9D and=
 then the non-regulatory-website-reading people will=C2=A0start singing it =
themselves and get it stuck in their heads, and then when they are targeted=
 for scams they will say =E2=80=9Cwait, I know a song about this=E2=80=9D a=
nd check the Financial Services Register? I don=E2=80=99t know, it=E2=80=99=
s no worse than any other financial-literacy theory really.Elsewhere, here =
is an op-ed in the Financial Times about financial literacy by Courtney Lov=
e.
