<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitcoin garbage guy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earlier this year we talked about a gu=
y in Wales named James Howells who threw out a hard drive with 8,000 Bitcoi=
ns on it back when Bitcoin was just a hobby, and now that those Bitcoins ar=
e worth hundreds of millions of dollars he is crusading to dig up the garba=
ge dump to find the hard drive. This is an irresistible subject for jokes, =
and I made some jokes about it that you can read <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25984731.270646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMTUvanBtb3JnYW4taGFkLWEtZ29vZC1iYWQ=
teWVhcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA5MjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEyMDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB69180c79" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25984731.270646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMTkvbWF5YmUtdGhlLWluZGV4LWZ1=
bmRzLWRvbi10LXZvdGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwOTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcebdc1c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a>.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/25984731.270646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2VyLmNvbS9tYWdhemluZS8=
yMDIxLzEyLzEzL2hhbGYtYS1iaWxsaW9uLWluLWJpdGNvaW4tbG9zdC1pbi10aGUtZHVtcA/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfe2d0f4a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a New Yorker profile</a> of the guy=
, who I think it is safe to say is=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>worse off for be=
ing a Bitcoin-millionaire-but-they=E2=80=99re-in-a-dump than he would be if=
 he had never had the thousands of Bitcoins:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">He told me that his children were into other things now, and =
didn=E2=80=99t visit anymore. He did not wish to discuss any romantic relat=
ionships that he=E2=80=99d had since Hafina left. =E2=80=9CI try to keep to=
 myself,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CWomen are costly.=E2=80=9D</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Howells was no longer employed. For more than a year=
 after the loss of the hard drive, he had continued at his job as a systems=
 engineer. To make the workday tolerable, he=E2=80=99d limited how often he=
 consulted the bitcoin-tracking app. He=E2=80=99d even tried to avoid drivi=
ng routes that took him by the dump. But, eventually, the memory of the mon=
ey he had thrown away overpowered his work ethic. =E2=80=9CI kind of lost t=
he motivation,=E2=80=9D he explained.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Also he constantly checks how much his lost Bitcoins are worth and=
=C2=A0worries he might get robbed because he=E2=80=99s a Bitcoin celebrity.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/25984731.270646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMDgvd2hhdC1kb2VzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZs=
b3ctYnV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDkyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB328af74b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> joked enough</a> about the =E2=
=80=9Cobject-fire-token-money=E2=80=9D cycle of non-fungible tokens to say =
that the obvious solution here is that Howells should mint a non-fungible t=
oken representing, like, =E2=80=9CI threw away 8,000 Bitcoins.=E2=80=9D Thi=
s would have two benefits:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; paddin=
g-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He=E2=
=80=99d own a tangible (ish) thing representing his Bitcoins in the dump, w=
hich might make him feel better, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Maybe he could sell it? Or a share of it? How much would an NFT represen=
ting 8,000 vanished Bitcoins be worth? Search me, but maybe something?</li>=
</ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But actually you don=E2=80=99t need to ge=
t into the metaphysics of NFTs to do this; this is just regular finance. Ri=
ght now Howells has some sort of=C2=A0<em>claim </em>to those lost Bitcoins=
. That claim is not worth 8,000 Bitcoins or anything close to it, because:<=
/p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px =
0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Nobody has possession of the hard =
drive; it=E2=80=99s somewhere in the dump.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Actually you can=E2=80=99t be 100% sure it=E2=80=99s even in the d=
ump? Maybe a seagull carried it away, or everyone=E2=80=99s memory of throw=
ing it in the dump is wrong, I don=E2=80=99t know.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">The town of Newport, which runs=C2=A0the dump, has emphati=
cally denied his requests to dig up the dump to find the hard drive and doe=
sn=E2=80=99t seem likely to budge on that.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Even if you did find it in the dump, it might have decayed to the =
point where his private key is not recoverable.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Even if the town authorities=C2=A0change their mind, he digs =
up the dump, he finds the hard drive, it works, his key is on it, and he re=
covers the 8,000 Bitcoins, many of those Bitcoins have been promised to som=
eone else at this point: =E2=80=9CHe met with potential investors, and even=
tually made arrangements with two European businessmen who agreed to suppor=
t a recovery operation. Howells would get only about a third of the proceed=
s. He had hoped for a much higher sum; the money was his, after all. He rec=
alls being told, =E2=80=98James, that=E2=80=99s not how it works.=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D (Also: =E2=80=9Che made a public offer to give Newport a twenty-f=
ive-per-cent cut of the proceeds=E2=80=9D if they approved his dig.)</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is not clear to me what his legal o=
wnership of the hard drive is; if I snuck into the dump at night, found the=
 hard drive myself and took it, could anyone demand it=C2=A0from me? It was=
 thrown away; who owns it? Or if I formed my own consortium of diggers and =
promised Newport a 50% cut of the proceeds, and Newport let me dig, would H=
owells have any claim to stop me?</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sti=
ll! Howells=E2=80=99s murky contingent residual claim =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9C<em>if </em>I get permission to dig up this dump and=C2=A0<em>if=C2=A0</=
em>I find this hard drive and=C2=A0<em>if</em> we find the=C2=A0Bitcoins on=
 it and=C2=A0<em>after </em>I pay off everyone else, I=E2=80=99ll have some=
 Bitcoins left=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems like it might be valuable? It =
is somewhat better than a lottery ticket. There is some imaginable future =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>he=C2=A0</em>certainly imagines it, and he=E2=80=99s con=
vinced some people to back him=C2=A0financially =E2=80=94=C2=A0where he act=
ually digs up the hard drive and gets (some of) the Bitcoins and his stake =
is worth, you know, $120 million. If there=E2=80=99s a 5% chance of that ha=
ppening then that chance is worth like $6 million. Maybe someone would pay =
him $3 million for a 50% share of his claim? He=E2=80=99s got a potentially=
 valuable asset, which, by the rules of finance, means that he=E2=80=99s go=
t an=C2=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>valuable asset.=C2=A0Why not sell it? Isn=
=E2=80=99t that better=C2=A0than hanging on to it obsessively?</p><table cl=
